[normal]Appendix to the written evidence submitted by National Farmers’ Union of England &amp; Wales (NFU) 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As stated in the full EFRA submission, the NFU believes that a
[normal]ll farmers want to avoid the problems of the previous CAP reform recurring. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The reality is that CAP receipts are an integral revenue stream for 
[normal]many farming businesses, with cash flow implications resulting from any inaccurate or delayed payments. The challenges faced by the industry back in 2005 are still recalled by many, with
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]accurate communication and certainty of payment particularly sought after by farmers. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Progress has been made in recent years to rectify the problems of SPS implementation. However, as new policy measures are introduced alongside shifts in delivery (e.g. digital by default), it is essential that changes do not undermine the validation and delivery of payments going forward. 
[normal]The below text elaborates on the issues flagged in the EFRA submission. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Currently there are no EU Commission implementing rules communicated to member states, yet we are aware DEFRA is now in the process of building their IT solution. Ideally, a new system would not be constructed until it
[normal]s
[normal] requirements are fully known. In practice, the timeframe for implementation and delivery of CAP is tight. It is therefore important that the system is flexible enough to adapt to last-minute changes. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]An increasing number of SPS applications have been undertaken online in the current programme period (currently approximately 55,000). This means that a relevant risk of the new IT system is how
[normal] farmers 
[normal]and agents will adapt to any 
[normal]change
[normal]s
[normal] to 
[normal]the 
[normal]online application process
[normal] alongside the new policy measures. A farmer friendly application process is integral to the success of implementing the new CAP. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clearly the next CAP must be delivered by a government department and its agencies that are required to contribute to efficiency savings. As a result, reductions in resource levels may coincide with a change in CAP policy that actually triggers increased demand for support. Online 
[normal]resources  offer
[normal] channels for more effective support, and it is critical that the operational knowledge gained through the current CAP is not lost as any resource efficiencies are implemented. 
[normal] 
[normal]Help
[normal] with the completion of claims in the first year is
[normal] likely to be
[normal] vital for those seeking assistance.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Delivery bodies need to offer multiple ways of engaging with farmers, road show events
[normal], etc
[normal];,
[normal] stakeholders have a key role in facilitating this farmer engagement. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The
[normal] online approach to applications 
[normal]has many benefits (reduced costs of administration, reduced errors, enhanced checking). However, some 
[normal]rural areas 
[normal]still 
[normal]find it difficult to apply online with the current rural broadband provision
[normal]. It remains unlikely that the rural
[normal] broadband situation will be resolved in the next 18 months.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We must ensure that connectivity restrictions do not make CAP schemes inaccessible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In conjunction with the IT systems, it is essential that 
[normal]validation processes 
[normal]are 
[normal]tested thoroughly prior to implementation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]In addition, based on previous experience, in-house expertise is preferable to a reliance on 
[normal]external developers 
[normal]to support IT and checking systems o
[normal]nce
[normal] they are
[normal] operating.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]hole claim validation carried out by as few staff as possible
[normal] would be the preference.
[normal] Task based working 
[normal]created many challenges
[normal] in the run up to 2005 payments being made.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]There remains scope to further
[normal] integrat
[normal]e Pillar 1 and 2 
[normal]validation
[normal]. Mapping issues have been well documented in the current programme, so
[normal] factoring in 
[normal]appropriate
[normal] resource to deal with the recording of greening is vital. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This will be required in all its forms and will be required from mid-2014 onwards to ensure that the industry is fully briefed ahead of the expected 2015 changeover of schemes
[normal], particularly in relation to
[normal] greening.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] All potential claimants will need a core base level of clear and user friendly information in 2015 and such information 
[normal]would ideally be provided
[normal] in paper form in the run up 
[normal]to the
[normal] first year of the new scheme
[normal]. 
[normal]There is a need to invest in the transition to the new schemes
[normal], which
[normal] 
[normal]can
[normal] be a platform to build on 
[normal]over time, 
[normal]in terms of value for money delivery – if farmers understand the new schemes
[normal] from the outset then there are likely to be fewer compliance issues, which 
[normal]helps minimise costs of validation, inspections
[normal], etc
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Agri
[normal]-environment schemes have been well received by famers, as demonstrated by the uptake. 
[normal]Yet a
[normal]s the scheme has developed
[normal], the 
[normal]detail has been refined either to clarify rules or 
[normal]ratchet up scheme requirements
[normal].  
[normal]For example, s
[normal]ince 2007 there have been 
[normal]3 scheme
[normal] handbooks issued capturing these changes. This has led to different rules applying depending on which date the agreement started.  Going forward there should be a clear ambition to get the scheme rules right from the outset and reduce the number of changes made through the lifespan of the agreements.
